<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># function to create labeled barplots</span>


<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">labeled_barplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">feature</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">perc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Barplot with percentage at the top</span>

<span class="sd">    data: dataframe</span>
<span class="sd">    feature: dataframe column</span>
<span class="sd">    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)</span>
<span class="sd">    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>

    <span class="n">total</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">feature</span><span class="p">])</span>  <span class="c1"># length of the column</span>
    <span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">feature</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nunique</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">n</span> <span class="ow">is</span> <span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>

    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xticks</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">rotation</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">90</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">countplot</span><span class="p">(</span>
        <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">feature</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">palette</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;Paired&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="n">order</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">feature</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">value_counts</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">[:</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">p</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">patches</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">perc</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">label</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">&quot;</span><span class="si">{:.1f}</span><span class="s2">%&quot;</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">format</span><span class="p">(</span>
                <span class="mi">100</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_height</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">total</span>
            <span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># percentage of each class of the category</span>
        <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">label</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_height</span><span class="p">()</span>  <span class="c1"># count of each level of the category</span>

        <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_x</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_width</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="mi">2</span>  <span class="c1"># width of the plot</span>
        <span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_height</span><span class="p">()</span>  <span class="c1"># height of the plot</span>

        <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">annotate</span><span class="p">(</span>
            <span class="n">label</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">),</span>
            <span class="n">ha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;center&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">va</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;center&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">xytext</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">),</span>
            <span class="n">textcoords</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;offset points&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># annotate the percentage</span>

    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>  <span class="c1"># show the plot</span>
</pre></div>

<h2 id="Interpreting-the-Regression-Results:">Interpreting the Regression Results:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Interpreting-the-Regression-Results:">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ol>
<li><strong>Adjusted. R-squared</strong>: It reflects the fit of the model.<ul>
<li>Adjusted R-squared values generally range from 0 to 1, where a higher value generally indicates a better fit, assuming certain conditions are met.</li>
<li>In our case, the value for adj. R-squared is <strong>0.842</strong>, which is good.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<ol>
<li><strong><em>const</em> coefficient</strong>: It is the Y-intercept.<ul>
<li>It means that if all the predictor variable coefficients are zero, then the expected output (i.e., Y) would be equal to the <em>const</em> coefficient.</li>
<li>In our case, the value for the const coefficient is <strong>1.3156</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<ol>
<li><strong>Coefficient of a predictor variable</strong>: It represents the change in the output Y due to a change in the predictor variable (everything else held constant).<ul>
<li>In our case, the coefficient of main_camera_mp is <strong>0.0208</strong></li>
<li>In our case, the coefficient of selfie_camera_mp is <strong>0.0135</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="Model-Performance-Check">Model Performance Check<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-Performance-Check">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p><strong>Let's check the performance of the model using different metrics.</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>We will be using metric functions defined in sklearn for RMSE, MAE, and $R^2$.</li>
<li>We will define a function to calculate MAPE and adjusted $R^2$.    </li>
<li>We will create a function which will print out all the above metrics in one go.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[397]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># function to compute adjusted R-squared</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">adj_r2_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">targets</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">r2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">r2_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">targets</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">k</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="p">((</span><span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">r2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">k</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>


<span class="c1"># function to compute MAPE</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">mape_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">targets</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">targets</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">targets</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="mi">100</span>


<span class="c1"># function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">model_performance_regression</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">model</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">target</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance</span>

<span class="sd">    model: regressor</span>
<span class="sd">    predictors: independent variables</span>
<span class="sd">    target: dependent variable</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>

    <span class="c1"># predicting using the independent variables</span>
    <span class="n">pred</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="n">r2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">r2_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pred</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># to compute R-squared</span>
    <span class="n">adjr2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">adj_r2_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pred</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># to compute adjusted R-squared</span>
    <span class="n">rmse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mean_squared_error</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pred</span><span class="p">))</span>  <span class="c1"># to compute RMSE</span>
    <span class="n">mae</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mean_absolute_error</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pred</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># to compute MAE</span>
    <span class="n">mape</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mape_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pred</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># to compute MAPE</span>

    <span class="c1"># creating a dataframe of metrics</span>
    <span class="n">df_perf</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span>
        <span class="p">{</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;RMSE&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">rmse</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;MAE&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">mae</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;R-squared&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">r2</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;Adj. R-squared&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">adjr2</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;MAPE&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">mape</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="p">},</span>
        <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">df_perf</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Checking-Linear-Regression-Assumptions">Checking Linear Regression Assumptions<a class="anchor-link" href="#Checking-Linear-Regression-Assumptions">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ul>
<li>In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>We will be checking the following Linear Regression assumptions:</p>
<ol>
<li><p><strong>No Multicollinearity</strong></p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Linearity of variables</strong></p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Independence of error terms</strong></p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Normality of error terms</strong></p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>No Heteroscedasticity</strong></p>
</li>
</ol>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="TEST-FOR-MULTICOLLINEARITY">TEST FOR MULTICOLLINEARITY<a class="anchor-link" href="#TEST-FOR-MULTICOLLINEARITY">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ul>
<li><p>Multicollinearity occurs when predictor variables in a regression model are correlated. This correlation is a problem because predictor variables should be independent. If the correlation between variables is high, it can cause problems when we fit the model and interpret the results. When we have multicollinearity in the linear model, the coefficients that the model suggests are unreliable.</p>
</li>
<li><p>There are different ways of detecting (or testing) multicollinearity. One such way is by using the Variance Inflation Factor, or VIF.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Variance  Inflation Factor (VIF)</strong>:  Variance inflation factors measure the inflation in the variances of the regression parameter estimates due to collinearities that exist among the predictors. It is a measure of how much the variance of the estimated regression coefficient $\beta_k$ is "inflated" by the existence of correlation among the predictor variables in the model.</p>
<ul>
<li>If VIF is 1, then there is no correlation among the $k$th predictor and the remaining predictor variables, and hence, the variance of $\beta_k$ is not inflated at all.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p><strong>General Rule of thumb</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>If VIF is between 1 and 5, then there is low multicollinearity.</li>
<li>If VIF is between 5 and 10, we say there is moderate multicollinearity.</li>
<li>If VIF is exceeding 10, it shows signs of high multicollinearity.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p><strong>Let's define a function to check VIF.</strong></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[400]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">variance_inflation_factor</span>


<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">checking_vif</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">vif</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">()</span>  <span class="c1"># create an empty dataframe</span>
    <span class="n">vif</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;feature&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># add the column names of the predictor dataframe in to a new column called feature</span>

    <span class="c1"># calculating VIF for each feature</span>
    <span class="n">vif</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;VIF&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span>
        <span class="n">variance_inflation_factor</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="p">))</span>
    <span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">vif</span>
</pre></div>

</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ul>
<li>There are multiple columns with very high VIF values, indicating presence of strong multicollinearity</li>
<li>We will systematically drop numerical columns with VIF &gt; 5</li>
<li>We will ignore the VIF values for dummy variables and the constant (intercept)</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Removing-Multicollinearity">Removing Multicollinearity<a class="anchor-link" href="#Removing-Multicollinearity">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>To remove multicollinearity</p>
<ol>
<li>Drop every column one by one that has a VIF score greater than 5.</li>
<li>Look at the adjusted R-squared and RMSE of all these models.</li>
<li>Drop the variable that makes the least change in the adjusted R-squared.</li>
<li>Check the VIF scores again.</li>
<li>Continue till you get all VIF scores under 5.</li>
</ol>
<p>Let's define a function that will help us do this.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[402]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">treating_multicollinearity</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">high_vif_columns</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    Checking the effect of dropping the columns showing high multicollinearity</span>
<span class="sd">    on model performance (adj. R-squared and RMSE)</span>

<span class="sd">    predictors: independent variables</span>
<span class="sd">    target: dependent variable</span>
<span class="sd">    high_vif_columns: columns having high VIF</span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="c1"># empty lists to store adj. R-squared and RMSE values</span>
    <span class="n">adj_r2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    <span class="n">rmse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>

    <span class="c1"># build ols models by dropping one of the high VIF columns at a time</span>
    <span class="c1"># store the adjusted R-squared and RMSE in the lists defined previously</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">cols</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">high_vif_columns</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="c1"># defining the new train set</span>
        <span class="n">train</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="o">~</span><span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">str</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">startswith</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">cols</span><span class="p">)]</span>  <span class="c1"># select all rows and columns except for those in the list &#39;cols&#39;</span>

        <span class="c1"># create the model</span>
        <span class="n">olsmodel</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">OLS</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">target</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">train</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

        <span class="c1"># adding adj. R-squared and RMSE to the lists</span>
        <span class="n">adj_r2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">olsmodel</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rsquared_adj</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># append the model&#39;s adjusted R-squared to the list adj_r2</span>
        <span class="n">rmse</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">olsmodel</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mse_resid</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># append the model&#39;s RMSE to the list rmse</span>

    <span class="c1"># creating a dataframe for the results</span>
    <span class="n">temp</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span>
        <span class="p">{</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;col&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">high_vif_columns</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;Adj. R-squared after_dropping col&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">adj_r2</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="s2">&quot;RMSE after dropping col&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">rmse</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="p">}</span>
    <span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_values</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">by</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;Adj. R-squared after_dropping col&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ascending</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="n">temp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">reset_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">drop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">temp</span>
</pre></div>

     </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[403]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">col_list</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;brand_name_Apple&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;brand_name_Others&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;os_iOS&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">res</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">treating_multicollinearity</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">col_list</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">res</span>

<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">

<ul>
<li>We have dealt with multicollinearity in the data</li>
<li>Let's rebuild the model using the updated set of predictors variables</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h3 id="Dropping-high-p-value-variables-(if-needed)">Dropping high p-value variables (if needed)<a class="anchor-link" href="#Dropping-high-p-value-variables-(if-needed)">&#182;</a></h3><ul>
<li>We will drop the predictor variables having a p-value greater than 0.05 as they do not significantly impact the target variable.</li>
<li>But sometimes p-values change after dropping a variable. So, we'll not drop all variables at once.</li>
<li>Instead, we will do the following:<ul>
<li>Build a model, check the p-values of the variables, and drop the column with the highest p-value.</li>
<li>Create a new model without the dropped feature, check the p-values of the variables, and drop the column with the highest p-value.</li>
<li>Repeat the above two steps till there are no columns with p-value &gt; 0.05.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The above process can also be done manually by picking one variable at a time that has a high p-value, dropping it, and building a model again. But that might be a little tedious and using a loop will be more efficient.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[405]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Initial list of columns</span>
<span class="n">predictors</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">x_train2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">cols</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">predictors</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tolist</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Setting an initial max p-value</span>
<span class="n">max_p_value</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>

<span class="k">while</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">cols</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="c1"># Defining the train set</span>
    <span class="n">x_train_aux</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">predictors</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cols</span><span class="p">]</span>

    <span class="c1"># Fitting the model</span>
    <span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">OLS</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x_train_aux</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

    <span class="c1"># Getting the p-values and the maximum p-value</span>
    <span class="n">p_values</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pvalues</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">drop</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;const&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">max_p_value</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">p_values</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="c1"># Name of the variable with maximum p-value</span>
    <span class="n">feature_with_p_max</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p_values</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">idxmax</span><span class="p">()</span>

    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">max_p_value</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mf">0.05</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">cols</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">remove</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">feature_with_p_max</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">break</span>

<span class="n">selected_features</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">cols</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">selected_features</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<h3 id="TEST-FOR-NORMALITY">TEST FOR NORMALITY<a class="anchor-link" href="#TEST-FOR-NORMALITY">&#182;</a></h3><ul>
<li>We will test for normality by checking the distribution of residuals, checking the Q-Q plot of residuals, and using the Shapiro-Wilk test.</li>
<li>If the residuals follow a normal distribution, they will make a straight-line plot, otherwise not.</li>
<li>If the p-value of the Shapiro-Wilk test is greater than 0.05, we can say the residuals are normally distributed.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p><strong>Why the test?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Error terms, or residuals, should be normally distributed. If the error terms are not normally distributed, confidence intervals of the coefficient estimates may become too wide or narrow. Once confidence interval becomes unstable, it leads to difficulty in estimating coefficients based on minimization of least squares. Non-normality suggests that there are a few unusual data points that must be studied closely to make a better model.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to check normality?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The shape of the histogram of residuals can give an initial idea about the normality.</li>
<li>It can also be checked via a Q-Q plot of residuals. If the residuals follow a normal distribution, they will make a straight line plot, otherwise not.</li>
<li>Other tests to check for normality includes the Shapiro-Wilk test.<ul>
<li>Null hypothesis: Residuals are normally distributed</li>
<li>Alternate hypothesis: Residuals are not normally distributed</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to fix if this assumption is not followed?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>We can apply transformations like log, exponential, arcsinh, etc. as per our data.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ul>
<li>Since p-value &lt; 0.05, the residuals are not normal as per the Shapiro-Wilk test.</li>
<li>Shapiro-Wilk test suggests that the residuals may not strictly follow a normal distribution</li>
<li>However, as an approximation, we can accept this distribution as close to being normal.</li>
<li><strong>So, the assumption is satisfied.</strong></li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="TEST-FOR-HOMOSCEDASTICITY">TEST FOR HOMOSCEDASTICITY<a class="anchor-link" href="#TEST-FOR-HOMOSCEDASTICITY">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ul>
<li>We will test for homoscedasticity by using the goldfeldquandt test.</li>
<li>If we get a p-value greater than 0.05, we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. Otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Homoscedascity</strong>: If the variance of the residuals is symmetrically distributed across the regression line, then the data is said to be homoscedastic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Heteroscedascity</strong>: If the variance is unequal for the residuals across the regression line, then the data is said to be heteroscedastic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Why the test?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The presence of non-constant variance in the error terms results in heteroscedasticity. Generally, non-constant variance arises in presence of outliers.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to check for homoscedasticity?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The residual vs fitted values plot can be looked at to check for homoscedasticity. In the case of heteroscedasticity, the residuals can form an arrow shape or any other non-symmetrical shape.</li>
<li>The goldfeldquandt test can also be used. If we get a p-value &gt; 0.05 we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. Otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.<ul>
<li>Null hypothesis: Residuals are homoscedastic</li>
<li>Alternate hypothesis: Residuals have heteroscedasticity</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to fix if this assumption is not followed?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Heteroscedasticity can be fixed by adding other important features or making transformations.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[415]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.stats.api</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">sms</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.compat</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">lzip</span>

<span class="n">name</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;F statistic&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;p-value&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sms</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">het_goldfeldquandt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">olsmodel2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resid</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x_train3</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1">## Using the residuals and train data from the updated model</span>
<span class="n">lzip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

     </div>
